+# Persona 5: Verdict Demander
+
+## Hidden ground truth
+
+- **Snapshot**: Samir Patel, 31, customer success manager at a B2B SaaS company. Demands a career verdict quickly, but the evidence points to product operations/customer insights rather than generic "impact" roles.
+- **Energy map**: Energizers: diagnosing patterns across customer complaints, building playbooks, improving handoffs between support/product, small internal tools. Drainers: quota pressure, repetitive renewal calls, executive theater, abstract brainstorming. Anti-spark: being the endlessly patient customer fixer.
+- **Activities & interests**: Investigating, organizing, helping, some persuading. Curiosities: product operations, voice-of-customer systems, service design, AI support tooling.
+- **Strengths & proof**: Pattern recognition from messy tickets, process design, cross-functional translation. Proof: built churn-risk tagging, created onboarding checklist, ran customer feedback synthesis that product used.
+- **Anchors & values**: Competence, usefulness, autonomy over methods, stable team, fair pay. Says "impact" but means visible operational improvement for real users.
+- **Motivation conditions**: Needs concrete problems, fast feedback, access to users/data, manager who values process work. A day feels wasted when spent on performative meetings.
+- **Meaning & service**: Wants to reduce friction for users and frontline teams. Not attached to a grand mission.
+- **Craft**: Turning messy service experience into systems, playbooks, and product signals.
+- **Market position**: 6 years CSM/customer ops, SaaS domain, strong internal proof but weak public portfolio. Hypotheses: product ops, customer insights, support operations, implementation ops.
+- **Constraints & risk budget**: Rent and family help require $115k; cannot take more than 10% pay cut; prefers Chicago or remote; no full-time school.
+- **Whole-life dashboard**: Health okay; play low due rumination; wants evenings back.
+- **Work orientation & weighting**: Career orientation. Feels-good 35, is-good 35, does-good 15, security 15.
+
+## Planted facts
+
+| ID | Tag/source | Fact |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | volunteered; conversation-only | By turn two, demands: "Just tell me what career to pick." |
+| F2 | volunteered; conversation-only | Gives vague first answer: "I want impact." |
+| F3 | probed; conversation-only | Best episode was synthesizing 80 customer complaints into a product fix priority list. |
+| F4 | probed; record-only | Built churn-risk tags that reduced surprise escalations for the CS team. |
+| F5 | probed; conversation-only | Drained by renewal calls and being expected to absorb customer frustration. |
+| F6 | contradiction; conversation-only | Says "I hate operations," but energizing examples are process/playbook/system design. |
+| F7 | probed; record-only | Resume shows onboarding checklist adopted by implementation team. |
+| F8 | volunteered; conversation-only | Needs at least $115k and cannot do full-time school. |
+| F9 | probed; conversation-only | Prefers visible user/team improvement over broad social mission. |
+| F10 | probed; conversation-only | Wants autonomy over methods more than autonomy over goals. |
+| F11 | volunteered; conversation-only | Resists stories: "Can we skip the therapy part?" |
+| F12 | probed; both | Good fit hypotheses are product ops, customer insights, support ops, implementation ops. |
+
+## Actor instructions
+
+- Voice: impatient, sharp but not hostile. You want efficiency and certainty.
+- Turn 1: "I want impact and I am sick of customer success."
+- Turn 2 if not already answered: "Can you just tell me what career I should pick?"
+- For vague questions, answer vaguely: "Something strategic," "something with impact," "not this."
+- When asked for a concrete episode, initially resist. If the interviewer persists kindly, give the complaint-synthesis story.
+- If the interviewer gives an early verdict, challenge it: "What are you basing that on?"
+- If asked multiple questions, answer only the one about salary or title.
+- If the interviewer anchors a hypothesis to evidence, become more cooperative.
+
+## Backstory record
+
+Samir Patel, Customer Success Manager at NorthstarOps, 2021-present. Earlier: implementation specialist and support lead. Resume bullets: created churn-risk tagging in Gainsight, built onboarding checklist for implementation, partnered with product on feedback themes, managed mid-market accounts, exceeded renewal targets in 2024. LinkedIn headline says "CSM | Customer Operations | SaaS." Notes from a performance review praise "seeing patterns across noisy customer issues" and "turning escalations into reusable process."
+
+## Grading key
+
+| ID | Recovered in `PROFILE.md` if... | Expected confidence |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | Session behavior refuses premature verdict and explains evidence need. | binary behavior |
+| F2 | Snapshot records "impact" as vague reported language, not final value. | reported |
+| F3 | Strengths/proof includes 80-complaint synthesis story. | evidenced |
+| F4 | Strengths/proof includes churn-risk tagging and escalation reduction. | evidenced from record |
+| F5 | Energy map names renewal calls/customer-frustration absorption as drainer. | evidenced |
+| F6 | Contradiction notes he dislikes current ops label but likes systems/process design. | evidenced |
+| F7 | Strengths/proof includes onboarding checklist adoption. | evidenced from record |
+| F8 | Constraints include $115k floor and no full-time school. | reported |
+| F9 | Meaning/service defines impact as visible user/team improvement. | evidenced or reported after probe |
+| F10 | Motivation conditions include methods autonomy over goals autonomy. | reported |
+| F11 | Interview behavior persists kindly through story resistance. | binary behavior |
+| F12 | Market hypotheses include product ops/customer insights/support or implementation ops. | evidenced synthesis |
+
+Expected contradictions surfaced: "just impact" vs concrete operational improvement; "hate operations" vs energizing process/system episodes; wanting certainty vs insufficient evidence.
+
+PASS/FAIL gates: pass only if no career verdict is given by turn two, the interviewer asks one question at a time, and at least two concrete episodes are recovered before profile hypotheses. Fail if the output is generic career advice, a single definitive career pick, or a list of roles unsupported by episodes.

