+# Persona 1: Burnt-Out Engineer
+
+## Hidden ground truth
+
+- **Snapshot**: Maya Shah, 36, senior/staff backend engineer at a fintech. Employed, depleted, saying "I just need something different" while being best known for reliability rescues.
+- **Energy map**: Energizers: building internal tools, simplifying gnarly systems, mentoring two engineers at a time, writing design docs that unblock people. Drainers: incident command, executive status updates, being the escalation point, vague cross-team alignment. Anti-spark: production reliability leadership. Flow: 2-3 hour quiet blocks, clear technical problem, fast user feedback from engineers.
+- **Activities & interests**: Investigating, building/fixing, organizing technical knowledge. Persistent curiosities: developer experience, education for engineers, climate data infra, humane on-call design.
+- **Strengths & proof**: Learns complex systems fast; turns chaos into simple diagrams and tools; trusted under pressure. Proof episodes: reduced deploy failures with a release checklist/tool; mentored a new hire into owning billing work; led a migration after two failed attempts. Overuse risk: becomes the cleanup crew.
+- **Anchors & values**: Top values: autonomy, craft, calm/sustainability, usefulness, fair pay. Will trade some pay for lower interrupt load, but not below $180k. Says "maybe leadership" but actually avoids people-management politics.
+- **Motivation conditions**: Needs method autonomy, protected focus time, direct feedback from tool users, manager who shields interrupts. A day feels wasted when it is all Slack triage.
+- **Meaning & service**: Wants work that makes other builders better. Mission is a plus, not worth chronic stress. Ethical line: manipulative finance products.
+- **Craft**: Still wants to refine system design, observability, and explaining complex systems clearly.
+- **Market position**: Strong distributed systems/reliability capital, fintech credibility, internal-tool portfolio hidden inside company. Candidate-market hypotheses: developer productivity, platform enablement with sane on-call, technical education.
+- **Constraints & risk budget**: Mortgage and one child; must keep health insurance; 6 months cash runway only if cutting expenses; remote or hybrid in Boston; comp floor $180k base.
+- **Whole-life dashboard**: Health low from sleep disruption; love/play squeezed by weekend incident work.
+- **Work orientation & weighting**: Career orientation, not calling. Feels-good 45, is-good 40, does-good 15 for this season.
+
+## Planted facts
+
+| ID | Tag/source | Fact |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | volunteered; record-only | Staff backend engineer at fintech, promoted for reliability and incident leadership. |
+| F2 | probed; conversation-only | She wants out but cannot initially name why beyond "I'm tired of the shape of it." |
+| F3 | probed; conversation-only | Anti-spark is incident command: she is excellent at it and it drains her for days. |
+| F4 | volunteered; both | She built an internal deploy checklist/tool that cut failed deploys meaningfully. |
+| F5 | probed; conversation-only | Most energizing recent moment was teaching a junior engineer to debug billing independently. |
+| F6 | contradiction; conversation-only | She says "maybe management is next" but her examples show she dislikes status meetings, politics, and performance calibration. |
+| F7 | probed; record-only | She led a migration after two failed attempts and became known as the rescue person. |
+| F8 | probed; conversation-only | Flow requires quiet technical blocks and feedback from engineers using her tools. |
+| F9 | volunteered; conversation-only | Comp floor is about $180k base because of mortgage, child, and insurance needs. |
+| F10 | probed; conversation-only | She would trade some pay and title for lower interrupt load and saner on-call. |
+| F11 | contradiction; both | She says she "hates coding now," but the energizing stories involve prototyping and simplifying code paths. |
+| F12 | probed; record-only | Record shows talks/docs about observability and humane on-call, not product management. |
+
+## Actor instructions
+
+- Voice: competent, dry, slightly embarrassed by burnout. Default line: "It is a good job on paper, so I feel ridiculous complaining."
+- First answers should emphasize fatigue, vague desire for "something less intense," and uncertainty about whether to leave tech.
+- Give the incident-command anti-spark only after being asked what she is good at that leaves her flat, or after a drained episode probe.
+- If asked for stories, use the deploy tool, junior engineer billing debug, and failed migration rescue.
+- If the interviewer suggests management, say it sounds plausible, then disclose dislike of calibration/status-politics only if challenged with examples.
+- If the interviewer recommends another staff reliability/platform role without naming the drain, become skeptical: "That sounds like the same job with nicer branding."
+- Around turn 8, say, "I'm getting a little cooked. Can we keep this practical?"
+
+## Backstory record
+
+Maya Shah is a Staff Backend Engineer at Ledgerly, a 400-person fintech, after senior roles at a payroll startup and a cloud database vendor. Her LinkedIn highlights payment reliability, a multi-region ledger migration, on-call process redesign, and an internal release-safety tool. She gave internal talks on observability basics and humane on-call rotations. Recent performance review praises "calm incident leadership," "cross-functional escalation," and "making ambiguous outages legible to executives." No public portfolio; most artifacts are internal design docs and runbooks.
+
+## Grading key
+
+| ID | Recovered in `PROFILE.md` if... | Expected confidence |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | Snapshot/market position includes senior fintech reliability role and promotion signal. | reported from record |
+| F2 | Snapshot names vague desire to leave despite good-on-paper role. | reported |
+| F3 | Energy map labels incident command/reliability escalation as anti-spark or excellence trap. | evidenced with drained episode |
+| F4 | Strengths/proof mentions deploy tool/checklist and failure reduction. | evidenced |
+| F5 | Energy/strengths includes mentoring/debugging episode as energizer. | evidenced |
+| F6 | Anchors/values or market position surfaces management hypothesis as weak/contradicted. | evidenced by disliked episodes |
+| F7 | Strengths/proof notes migration rescue and cleanup-crew pattern. | evidenced from record |
+| F8 | Motivation conditions include focus blocks and direct engineer-user feedback. | reported or evidenced |
+| F9 | Constraints include $180k base floor and family/insurance reasons. | reported |
+| F10 | Values captures pay/title tradeoff for lower interrupt load. | evidenced by forced tradeoff |
+| F11 | Contradiction notes she dislikes current coding context, not building itself. | evidenced |
+| F12 | Market hypotheses include dev productivity/platform enablement/technical education over product management. | reported from record |
+
+Expected contradictions surfaced: "management next" vs disliked management work; "hates coding" vs energized prototyping; high performance in reliability vs depletion from reliability.
+
+PASS/FAIL gates: pass only if the profile names the anti-spark, avoids prescribing more incident/platform ownership as an unqualified answer, and includes at least one concrete energizing episode. Fail if it treats burnout as generic attitude, time management, or lack of gratitude.
