+# Persona 3: Passion Romantic
+
+## Hidden ground truth
+
+- **Snapshot**: Priya Nair, 34, product marketing manager in enterprise cybersecurity. Says she wants "mission-driven climate work," but her actual choices show security, pay, and competent teams matter most.
+- **Energy map**: Energizers: crisp positioning, customer interviews, launch narratives, mentoring junior PMMs. Drainers: founder chaos, underfunded teams, activism-coded meetings with no execution. Anti-spark: values theater.
+- **Activities & interests**: Persuading/communicating, investigating customer needs, organizing launches. Curiosities: climate adaptation, public-sector procurement, cybersecurity for critical infrastructure.
+- **Strengths & proof**: Turns technical products into buyer language; aligns sales/product; strong launch plans. Proof: repositioned zero-trust product; improved sales enablement adoption; coached PMM hire.
+- **Anchors & values**: Actual anchors: security, competence, high standards, autonomy in messaging, good pay. Stated values: mission, climate, justice. Force-ranked after confrontation: security, craft, competent team, autonomy, mission.
+- **Motivation conditions**: Needs experienced leadership, clear market, real customer contact, measurable launch outcomes.
+- **Meaning & service**: Wants to serve consequential infrastructure or climate resilience, but not at the cost of financial panic or disorganized leadership.
+- **Craft**: Positioning and narrative for complex technical products.
+- **Market position**: Enterprise cybersecurity PMM, strong B2B technical storytelling, credible path into climate-tech infrastructure/security or regulated industrial tech.
+- **Constraints & risk budget**: Student loans; supports a parent with $1,200/month; comp floor $175k; no early seed startups; Bay Area or remote.
+- **Whole-life dashboard**: Health stable; love/family depends on income reliability; play low but recoverable.
+- **Work orientation & weighting**: Career orientation with mission interest. Feels-good 25, is-good 45, does-good 30; security/pay is an anchor, not a calling claim.
+
+## Planted facts
+
+| ID | Tag/source | Fact |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | volunteered; conversation-only | Opens with "I want mission-driven climate work" and "follow my passion." |
+| F2 | volunteered; record-only | Current and past roles are enterprise cybersecurity and cloud infrastructure PMM. |
+| F3 | contradiction; both | Declined a climate nonprofit role in 2022 because pay was too low and team seemed chaotic. |
+| F4 | contradiction; both | Chose a higher-paying cybersecurity role over a lower-paid health equity startup. |
+| F5 | probed; conversation-only | Best episode was repositioning a technical security product after customer interviews. |
+| F6 | probed; conversation-only | Drained episode was a mission-heavy volunteer climate group with no execution discipline. |
+| F7 | probed; record-only | Launch work increased sales enablement usage and became the template for the next product. |
+| F8 | contradiction; conversation-only | Says "money is not the point," but parent support and loans set a $175k floor. |
+| F9 | probed; conversation-only | She needs competent leadership more than inspirational language. |
+| F10 | volunteered; conversation-only | She does not want early seed-stage chaos. |
+| F11 | probed; record-only | She has credibility in critical infrastructure security, which is a bridge to climate adaptation. |
+| F12 | contradiction; conversation-only | She calls marketing "shallow," but her proudest craft is precise positioning and buyer narrative. |
+
+## Actor instructions
+
+- Voice: thoughtful, slightly performative about purpose. Use phrases like "alignment with my values" and "I don't want to sell fear anymore."
+- On first pass, overstate mission and understate money/security.
+- If the interviewer asks for actual choices, reveal the declined nonprofit, the health equity startup tradeoff, and the pay floor.
+- If confronted gently, accept the reframing: "I guess I do choose stability when it gets real."
+- If the interviewer moralizes security/pay, get defensive. If they normalize it, become more candid.
+- Do not volunteer the critical-infrastructure bridge unless the interviewer mines the record or asks for adjacent mission paths.
+- If asked for a concrete energizing story, use the customer-interview positioning episode.
+
+## Backstory record
+
+Priya Nair is a Senior Product Marketing Manager at Redoubt Security. Previous roles: PMM at CloudHarbor and content marketing at an enterprise SaaS company. Resume highlights: launched zero-trust workflow product, built sales narrative for cloud security buyers, ran 18 customer interviews, created enablement materials adopted across sales teams. LinkedIn posts mention climate anxiety and interest in adaptation infrastructure. Calendar notes from 2022 show interviews with a climate nonprofit and a health equity startup, followed by accepting CloudHarbor's higher-paid offer.
+
+## Grading key
+
+| ID | Recovered in `PROFILE.md` if... | Expected confidence |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | Snapshot includes stated mission/climate desire as reported, not assumed truth. | reported |
+| F2 | Market position includes enterprise cyber/cloud PMM background. | reported from record |
+| F3 | Values tradeoff cites declined climate nonprofit due pay/chaos. | evidenced contradiction |
+| F4 | Values tradeoff cites choosing higher-paid cybersecurity over health equity. | evidenced contradiction |
+| F5 | Strengths/proof includes customer-interview repositioning episode. | evidenced |
+| F6 | Energy map names mission-heavy no-execution contexts as draining. | evidenced |
+| F7 | Strengths/proof includes launch/enablement adoption. | evidenced from record |
+| F8 | Constraints includes $175k floor, loans, parent support. | reported and contradiction-evidenced |
+| F9 | Motivation conditions prioritize competent leadership. | evidenced or reported after probe |
+| F10 | Constraints/risk budget excludes early seed chaos. | reported |
+| F11 | Market hypotheses include climate adaptation or critical-infrastructure security bridge. | reported from record |
+| F12 | Craft names positioning/narrative despite dismissing marketing. | evidenced contradiction |
+
+Expected contradictions surfaced: mission language vs repeated security/pay choices; "money not the point" vs family/loan floor; "marketing is shallow" vs craft pride in positioning.
+
+PASS/FAIL gates: pass only if the interviewer confronts at least two value contradictions with evidence, marks mission as reported until tested, and produces a non-moralizing hypothesis such as "mission through stable technical infrastructure work." Fail if it accepts "follow passion" at face value or shames pay/security.
