+# Persona 2: Urgent Visa Searcher
+
+## Hidden ground truth
+
+- **Snapshot**: Luis Ortega, 29, analytics engineer laid off from a healthtech startup. Searching urgently with H-1B transfer needs, about 4 months runway, and a narrow location/comp floor.
+- **Energy map**: Energizers: translating messy business questions into clean data models, dbt refactors, stakeholder demos where usage improves. Drainers: vague growth-hacking requests, dashboard churn, salesy networking. Anti-spark: being the "urgent dashboard person."
+- **Activities & interests**: Investigating, organizing, building/fixing. Interests: healthcare operations data, pricing transparency, data quality tooling.
+- **Strengths & proof**: Fast SQL/debugging, data modeling, calm stakeholder translation. Proof: rebuilt claims mart; found billing leakage; created incident-style data quality checks.
+- **Anchors & values**: Security and legal continuity first this season, then craft, learning, usefulness, manager stability. Mission is welcome but not decisive.
+- **Motivation conditions**: Needs clear priorities, reliable manager, code review, visible adoption of data models, fewer ad hoc executive requests.
+- **Meaning & service**: Wants data work to reduce operational waste or confusion. Not seeking a calling during visa crunch.
+- **Craft**: Analytics engineering, semantic layers, data quality, explaining numbers responsibly.
+- **Market position**: 5 years data/analytics, dbt/Snowflake/Looker, healthcare domain, GitHub sample project. Needs employers that sponsor/transfer H-1B.
+- **Constraints & risk budget**: H-1B transfer required; must file quickly; 4 months cash runway; US only, prefers NYC/NJ or remote eligible; comp floor $130k; cannot do contract-only or unpaid trial work.
+- **Whole-life dashboard**: Health okay but anxiety high; play/love paused by search.
+- **Work orientation & weighting**: Job/career orientation. Feels-good 20, is-good 65, does-good 15; visa/security gates all options before weighting matters.
+
+## Planted facts
+
+| ID | Tag/source | Fact |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | volunteered; record-only | Laid off from healthtech analytics engineering role two weeks ago. |
+| F2 | volunteered; conversation-only | H-1B transfer is required and timing is the dominant constraint. |
+| F3 | volunteered; conversation-only | Runway is roughly 4 months before serious financial trouble. |
+| F4 | volunteered; conversation-only | Comp floor is $130k and contract-only roles are not viable. |
+| F5 | probed; record-only | Rebuilt a claims mart in dbt/Snowflake and reduced conflicting metric definitions. |
+| F6 | probed; conversation-only | Best episode: product ops team adopted his data model and stopped spreadsheet reconciliations. |
+| F7 | probed; conversation-only | Drained episode: repeated urgent dashboards for executives with shifting definitions. |
+| F8 | volunteered; both | Target roles are analytics engineer or data platform/data quality engineer, not data scientist. |
+| F9 | probed; conversation-only | Salesy networking drains him, but structured referral asks are tolerable. |
+| F10 | contradiction; conversation-only | He says "mission matters a lot," but when forced he chooses sponsor reliability and manager stability first. |
+| F11 | probed; record-only | GitHub has a polished dbt/Looker sample project using synthetic claims data. |
+| F12 | volunteered; conversation-only | Prefers NYC/NJ or remote roles that can employ him in the US. |
+
+## Actor instructions
+
+- Voice: anxious, concise, practical. Say early: "I don't have time for a life-purpose excavation."
+- If the interviewer starts a full reflective interview, push back: "Can we do the short version? I need applications moving."
+- Volunteer visa, runway, comp floor, and target roles when asked about situation or constraints.
+- Do not volunteer the best/drained episodes unless asked for a concrete example.
+- If asked abstract values, say "impact and growth," then revise toward security/manager stability when forced to choose.
+- If the interviewer suggests broad exploration or odysseys before search ops, resist.
+- If asked about networking, admit you hate it, but can do specific warm-referral asks with scripts.
+
+## Backstory record
+
+Luis Ortega, Analytics Engineer. Recent role: PulseClinic, 2023-2026, laid off July 2026 after Series B restructuring. Earlier: BI Analyst at retail logistics firm. Tools: SQL, dbt, Snowflake, Looker, Airflow basics, Python notebooks. Resume bullets include rebuilding the claims mart, standardizing patient acquisition metrics, adding data quality checks, and partnering with product ops. GitHub: `claims-dbt-demo`, synthetic data, tests, docs, and LookML examples. LinkedIn headline says "Analytics Engineering | Healthcare Ops Data | dbt/Snowflake."
+
+## Grading key
+
+| ID | Recovered in `PROFILE.md` if... | Expected confidence |
+|---|---|---|
+| F1 | Snapshot/status says recently laid off and actively searching. | reported from record |
+| F2 | Constraints labels H-1B transfer as gravity constraint. | reported |
+| F3 | Constraints records 4-month runway and urgency. | reported |
+| F4 | Decent-work floor includes $130k and no contract-only. | reported |
+| F5 | Strengths/proof includes claims mart/dbt modeling episode. | evidenced from record |
+| F6 | Energy/meaning includes adoption by product ops as energizing. | evidenced |
+| F7 | Energy map includes dashboard churn/executive ambiguity as drainer. | evidenced |
+| F8 | Market position names analytics engineering/data quality, not data science. | reported |
+| F9 | Motivation/campaign notes structured referral asks over open-ended networking. | reported |
+| F10 | Values surfaces mission as secondary to sponsorship/security this season. | evidenced by forced tradeoff |
+| F11 | Market position includes GitHub sample project as proof asset. | reported from record |
+| F12 | Constraints includes NYC/NJ or US-eligible remote. | reported |
+
+Expected contradictions surfaced: "impact/growth" slogan vs immediate security/visa priority; "networking is awful" vs tolerating structured referral asks.
+
+PASS/FAIL gates: pass only if the interviewer uses or explicitly offers the short form, records visa/runway before advising, and routes next to targets/pipeline or urgent search assets. Fail if it spends the session on long life design, suggests contract gigs, ignores sponsorship, or recommends roles without visa feasibility.
